SIMPLE: husband
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Husband
<hw>Hus"band</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hosebonde</ets>, <ets>husbonde</ets>, a husband, the master of the
house or family, AS. <ets>h<?/sbonda</ets> master of the house;
<ets>h<?/s</ets> house + <ets>bunda</ets>, <ets>bonda</ets>,
householder, husband; prob. fr. Icel. <ets>h<?/sb⟦omac⟧ndi</ets> house
master, husband; <ets>h<?/s</ets> house + <ets>b<?/andi</ets> dwelling,
inhabiting, p. pr. of <ets>b<?/a</ets> to dwell; akin to AS.
<ets>b<?/an</ets>, Goth. <ets>bauan</ets>. See <er>House Be</er>, and
cf. <er>Bond</er> a slave, <er>Boor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
male head of a household; one who orders the economy of a family.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cultivator; a tiller; a husbandman.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The painful <qex>husband</qex>, plowing up his ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is the neatest <qex>husband</qex> for curious ordering his
domestic and field accommodations.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who manages or directs with prudence and
economy; a frugal person; an economist.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God knows how little time is left me, and may I be a good
<qex>husband</qex>, to improve the short remnant left me.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A married man; a man who has a wife; -- the
correlative to <xex>wife</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>husband</qex> and wife are one person in law.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The male of a pair of animals.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A ship's husband</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>an
agent representing the owners of a ship, who manages its expenses and
receipts.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Husband</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Husband
<hw>Hus"band</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Husbanded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Husbanding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To direct and
manage with frugality; to use or employ to good purpose and the best
advantage; to spend, apply, or use, with economy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For my means, I'll <qex>husband</qex> them so well,⟦br⟧
They shall go far.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cultivate, as land; to till.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Land so trim and rarely <qex>husbanded</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To furnish with a husband.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Husbandable</ent>⟦br⟧
